UPDATE questions SET question_text = $q$The student wants to explain how Champollion reached and announced his breakthrough in reading Egyptian texts. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?$q$, options = $j$[{"id":"A","text":"By comparing the Demotic names inscribed on the stone to their Greek spellings, Champollion proved in his 1822 letter that the Rosetta Stone's three different scripts had each been used to record an entirely separate royal decree rather than one shared text.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Unwarranted Synthesis: Fabricates different decrees and the wrong script comparison."},{"id":"B","text":"Champollion's celebrated 1822 letter announced to the scholarly world that he had at last achieved a long-sought breakthrough in the reading of ancient Egyptian texts written in the hieroglyphic script, a feat that had eluded earlier scholars for centuries.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Goal Under Specification: Names the announcement but omits how the breakthrough was reached."},{"id":"C","text":"By systematically comparing the Greek versions of royal names on the Rosetta Stone to their corresponding hieroglyphic spellings, Champollion argued that hieroglyphs could represent sounds and not only ideas, and his 1822 letter announced this hard-won breakthrough in the reading of ancient Egyptian texts.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Uses only the notes to accomplish the stated goal without overstatement or outside claims."},{"id":"D","text":"Champollion's celebrated 1822 letter announced to the scholarly world that Egyptian hieroglyphs were in fact a purely symbolic picture writing, thereby confirming the very assumption that earlier generations of scholars had long held about the ancient script.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Truth without Goal: Contradicts his argument that hieroglyphs could represent sounds."}]$j$::jsonb, correct_answer = 'C', explanation = $e$Goal: explain how Champollion reached and announced his breakthrough in reading Egyptian texts.

