UPDATE questions SET question_text = $q$The student wants to trace penicillin's development from discovery through an early obstacle to its wartime availability. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?$q$, options = $j$[{"id":"A","text":"In 1928, Alexander Fleming identified the Penicillium mold growing on a contaminated petri dish and gave the name penicillin to the antibacterial substance that the mold was visibly producing against the surrounding bacteria.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Goal Under Specification: Covers the discovery but omits the obstacle and wartime availability the goal requires."},{"id":"B","text":"After Alexander Fleming named penicillin in 1928, the substance's unstable initial extracts proved difficult to mass-produce until Howard Florey and Ernst Chain developed methods to purify and scale it, ultimately making the antibiotic widely available to Allied forces during World War II.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Uses only the notes to accomplish the stated goal without overstatement or outside claims."},{"id":"C","text":"Penicillin became widely available to Allied forces during World War II only after Alexander Fleming, working entirely on his own, had perfected a stable and easily mass-produced extract of the new antibiotic back in 1928, well before any other researchers became involved.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Truth without Goal: Credits Fleming with the scaling that the notes attribute to Florey and Chain."},{"id":"D","text":"Howard Florey and Ernst Chain discovered penicillin themselves and, facing no real production obstacles of any kind, were able to distribute the finished antibiotic to Allied forces throughout the later years of World War II.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Unwarranted Synthesis: Erases the documented instability obstacle and misattributes the discovery."}]$j$::jsonb, correct_answer = 'B', explanation = $e$Goal: trace penicillin's development from discovery through an early obstacle to its wartime availability.

